 before the main method. But wait, if the native image can’t launch Java, is there an alternative? I think about using ProcessBuilder, but I wonder if the native image lacks a Java binary, which doesn't seem ideal. Another thought is adding a test class in the same file or using @BeforeAll, but that timing might not work. Setting a Gradle system property in build.gradle to safe=true for all tests is also an option.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying module reading**\\n\\nI'm considering if the module `addReads` should execute when the source named `auto module` can’t read the target that’s unnamed. I’m mulling over how automatic modules interact with named and unnamed ones. It seems automatic modules can read all named modules, but I'm unsure about unnamed ones. The `JavaModule.canRead` method might indicate if an automatic module can read, leading to some conditions for reads. Perhaps creating a synthetic module could be a solution, or defining a module with classes from the jar.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering testing structure**\\n\\nThe user mentioned keeping tests outside of library packages, particularly with a note about a helper not being a \\\"test.\\\" I see some risk there, but it seems wise to ensure coverage. I might need to create a helper in org.modelmapper.internal.bytebuddy.dynamic. However, for \\\"one-to-one mapping test files,\\\" should I add a helper file for the active class instead? The guideline specifies that coverage should be in its own dedicated Java test file under src/test/java.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_hTQdKWv6WJ4kclJs8Ez825wt|fc_0a523461cc4321fa0169f17ff7295081a1af73eaaf23198c81", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.modelmapper/modelmapper/3.2.0/7664b15466a898625b394af6000439c5799a5d2b/modelmapper-3.2.0.jar -p 'org.modelmapper.internal.bytebuddy.dynamic.loading.ClassInjector$UsingReflection$Dispatcher